Hydroxyurea in patients with falciform syndroms assisted at Hemope Hospital, Recife-PE
The falciform syndroms (FS) comprise a set of haemoglobin qualitative disorders in which the S haemoglobin gene is inherited. [1] Among these, the most frequent one is the falciform anemia (SS homozygosis), whose patients have organic damages since their childhood, resulting from repeated vaso-occlusive episodes. [2] Several studies on adults have shown the efficiency of the use of hydroxyurea (HU), whose main effect is the increase in fetal hemoglobine levels (HbF) in patients with FS with little or no side effect. [3, 4, 5, 6] HU is a chemical therapeutical agent well known and used for the treatment of myeloproliferative syndroms such as chronical myeloid leukemia and polycythemia vera. Its main function is to block the DNA synthesis by inhibiting the ribonucleotide reductase, keeping the cells in the S phase. [1] It is easily used, with few toxic side effects and with an easily reversible myelosupression effect. The use of hydroxyurea in the treatment of falciform anemia (FA) began in the 1980's, in adult patients; it was later authorized to be used in children. [7] Along the years, studies on children have shown the same efficiency of the use of HU with no significant side effects. [2, 7, 8, 9, 10] Thus, the present study has the purpose to investigate, through a series of cases, the efficiency of the use of HU and its tolerance by FS patients in the pediatric stage and young adults, as well as to evaluate the variations in hematological parameters in both age groups and in HbF values in the pediatric group.
